{"type":"message","id":"a9278e4d","parentId":"77e93e0c","timestamp":"2026-06-03T23:01:12.640Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-93dac0fe393afb35","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/workspace/ground_truth/Agentic_Sandbox_Ground_Truth.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"path\": \"/home/node/workspace/ground_truth/Agentic_Sandbox_Ground_Truth.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"vllm","model":"RedHatAI/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct-FP8-dynamic","usage":{"input":14840,"output":31,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14871,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780527665222,"responseId":"chatcmpl-ba775604c933e3f7"}}
{"type":"message","id":"0acb6b27","parentId":"a9278e4d","timestamp":"2026-06-03T23:01:12.645Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-93dac0fe393afb35","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Agentic Sandbox Project (AIOS) - Ground Truth Reference Document\n\n## 1. Project Vision and Motivation\n* **Core Concept**: Design and build an industry-informed agentic innovation infrastructure, referred to as an Agentic Operating System (AIOS) or \"Sandbox\".\n* **Vision**: Create a controlled, isolated environment where deployed AI agents can execute tasks (perceive, reason, act) and collaborate with other agents without producing unintended consequences or affecting real-world enterprise systems.\n* **Motivation**: As organizations shift towards enterprise systems composed of multiple autonomous agents, the Sandbox answers a critical architectural question: *How do we architect these systems well?* It allows organizations to safely address \"what-if\" scenarios. Furthermore, it facilitates the translation of university-based AI inventions into practical industry solutions.\n* **Target Partners**: University researchers, industry organizations, non-profit organizations, and government entities.\n\n## 2. Core Features and Capabilities\nThe AIOS Sandbox will be designed to offer the following high-level capabilities:\n* **Multi-Agent Simulation**: Simulate complex AI solutions composed of a network of collaborating AI agents.\n* **Workflow Orchestration**: Orchestrate complex, multistep workflows with intricate dependencies, all driven by a defined goal or outcome.\n* **Architecture Optimization**: Provide system-level goal-seeking capabilities to optimize agentic architectures and address architectural design flaws.\n* **Continuous Improvement**: Enable self-improving mechanisms via reinforcement learning (RL) and human observation.\n* **Risk Evaluation**: Simulate and evaluate cyber risk metrics specific to multi-agent environments.\n* **Explainability & Agency**: Implement built-in capabilities to address and ensure AI explainability and maintain proper agent agency.\n* **Human Team Mirroring**: Foster widespread adoption of sophisticated multi-agent systems equipped with specialized skills that mirror human team dynamics.\n\n## 3. System Architecture & Context\nThe infrastructure of the Agentic Sandbox is conceptualized through the following layers:\n* **Computing Infrastructure**: Built upon an advanced or enhanced selection of open-source frameworks.\n* **Agentic OS / Infrastructure**: The core engine managing the deployment, integration, and execution of autonomous agents.\n* **Input Streams**:\n    * *Business/Societal Challenges*: Use cases driven by industry, non-profits, and government entities.\n    * *Agentic Innovations*: Single or multi-agent research models generated by RIT AI Research and university partners.\n* **Industry Verticals**: Integration of specialized industry capabilities and skills.\n\n**RIT Strategic Pipeline (Translation)**\nA major theme of the project is bridging the gap between theoretical academia and industry. The project supports RIT's strategic direction of driving practice-inspired AI research. It aims to translate new algorithms and faculty-led research (inventions) into tangible commercial and societal artifacts through the university's entrepreneurial ecosystem and technology transfer offices.\n\n## 4. Research Directions, Milestones, & State of the Art\n### Immediate Summer Goals\n* **Vision Paper**: The primary end-of-summer objective is to author a vision paper describing the Agentic Sandbox. This will define the agent OS, detail key functions/requirements, map out the technical systems architecture, highlight 2-3 representative use cases, and outline next steps.\n* **Prototyping & Infrastructure Evaluation**: \n    * Survey and evaluate leading infrastructure and tools for agent building and deployment (e.g., OpenClaw, Manus, OpenAI Operator). Compare and contrast these tools.\n    * Build a prototype agent to demonstrate infrastructure capabilities (led by a summer student).\n* **Use Case Identification**: Establish 2-3 specific scenarios to test the infrastructure. Current targeted domains include:\n    * Healthcare\n    * Cyber risks in multi-agentic systems\n\n### Fall Goals\n* Deepen engagement with partner universities and industry stakeholders.\n* Develop a formal funding proposal for agencies such as NIST and/or NSF.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Evaluation Criteria for Research Papers (Agent Ground Truth)\n*When using an LLM agent to review and compare research literature against this project, papers should be evaluated on their relevance to the following core investigation areas:*\n\n1. **Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols**: Literature discussing emerging communication protocols and standards between autonomous agents.\n2. **Workflow Orchestration**: Frameworks and methods for the construction and orchestration of multi-agent workflows.\n3. **System-Level Intent & Recommendation**: System-level approaches for building architectures (e.g., *From Intent to Execution: Composing Agentic Workflows with Agent Recommendations* / AutoMAS).\n4. **Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)**: The application of Reinforcement Learning (RL) and control-theoretic approaches for creating adaptive, self-improving agentic systems.\n5. **Systems Theory**: The utilization of general systems theory in the design and building of AI agent-based systems."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1780527672645}}
